{#
Dummy Content for the Tips & Techniques Page.
Uses Tailwind CSS for a clean, readable layout.
#}
{% extends 'base.html.twig' %}
{% block body %}
    {# Main Content Container #}
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto py-12 px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">

        {# Page Title #}
        <h1 class="text-4xl font-extrabold text-[#1a1a1a] mb-4 border-b-2 border-gray-100 pb-2">
            Tips & Techniques: Elevate Your Cooking
        </h1>
        <p class="text-xl text-gray-600 mb-10">
            Essential guidance and pro-tips to help every home cook master their kitchen skills.
        </p>

        {# Section 1: Knife Skills #}
        <div class="mb-12">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-[#333333] mb-6">1. Knife Skills: The Foundation of Prep</h2>

            <div class="space-y-6">
                {# Tip 1 #}
                <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg shadow-md border-t-4 border-[#9b59b6]">
                    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-[#1a1a1a] mb-2">The Claw Grip (Safety First)</h3>
                    <p class="text-gray-700">
                        Always **curl your fingertips inward**, holding the food with your knuckles flat against the
                        knife blade. This acts as a shield, protecting your fingers and ensuring uniform, consistent
                        cuts.
                    </p>
                </div>

                {# Tip 2 #}
                <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg shadow-md border-t-4 border-gray-300">
                    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-[#1a1a1a] mb-2">Sharpen Often, Hone Daily</h3>
                    <p class="text-gray-700">
                        Use a **honing steel** (the rod) before every cooking session to realign the edge of your blade.
                        Use a **whetstone or sharpener** (to remove metal) only every few months when the knife is truly
                        dull.
                    </p>
                </div>

                {# Tip 3 #}
                <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg shadow-md border-t-4 border-gray-300">
                    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-[#1a1a1a] mb-2">The Rocking Motion</h3>
                    <p class="text-gray-700">
                        For herbs and smaller vegetables, use a smooth **rocking motion**, keeping the tip of the knife
                        in contact with the cutting board. This minimizes bruising and maximizes efficiency.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        {# Section 2: Mastering Basic Flavor #}
        <div class="mb-12">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-[#333333] mb-6">2. Mastering Basic Flavor</h2>

            {# Pro Tip Box (using accent color) #}
            <div class="bg-[#f9f0fd] border-l-4 border-[#9b59b6] p-4 mb-8 rounded-r-lg">
                <p class="text-lg font-medium text-gray-800">
                    <span class="font-bold text-[#9b59b6]">Pro Tip:</span> The key to almost every dish is balancing the
                    5 tastes. Taste your food *before* serving and adjust these four ingredients: **Salt**, **Acid**
                    (lemon, vinegar), **Sweet** (sugar, honey), and **Heat** (pepper, chili).
                </p>
            </div>

            {# Flavor Tips Grid #}
            <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8">
                {# Tip: Layering Salt #}
                <div>
                    <h4 class="text-xl font-semibold text-[#1a1a1a] mb-2">Layer Your Salt</h4>
                    <p class="text-gray-700">
                        Don't add all the salt at the end. Season meats and vegetables at the **beginning** of cooking,
                        season sauces and liquids in the **middle**, and adjust one last time right before serving.
                    </p>
                </div>

                {# Tip: Aromatics #}
                <div>
                    <h4 class="text-xl font-semibold text-[#1a1a1a] mb-2">Aromatics: Start Cold with Oil</h4>
                    <p class="text-gray-700">
                        When sautéing garlic and onions, start them in a **cold pan** with oil, then turn up the heat
                        gradually. This gently draws out their flavor and prevents the garlic from burning.
                    </p>
                </div>

                {# Tip: Herb Ratio #}
                <div>
                    <h4 class="text-xl font-semibold text-[#1a1a1a] mb-2">Fresh vs. Dried Herb Rule</h4>
                    <p class="text-gray-700">
                        The standard conversion is a **3-to-1 ratio**. If a recipe calls for 1 teaspoon of **dried
                        herbs**, substitute it with 1 tablespoon of **fresh herbs**.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        {# Section 3: Essential Techniques #}
        <div class="mb-12">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-[#333333] mb-6">3. Essential Cooking Techniques</h2>

            <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-4 text-gray-700 pl-4">
                <li class="font-medium text-[#1a1a1a]">Searing and Deglazing
                    <p class="text-sm font-normal text-gray-600 mt-1">
                        Ensure your pan is **hot** and your protein is **dry** to get a perfect crust. After searing,
                        pour in a liquid (stock or wine) to scrape up the browned bits (**fond**) for an instant,
                        flavorful sauce.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li class="font-medium text-[#1a1a1a]">Don't Crowd the Pan
                    <p class="text-sm font-normal text-gray-600 mt-1">
                        When searing or sautéing, if you overload the pan, the temperature drops and the food will
                        **steam** instead of browning. Work in small batches if needed.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li class="font-medium text-[#1a1a1a]">Rest Your Meat
                    <p class="text-sm font-normal text-gray-600 mt-1">
                        After roasting or grilling, always let meat rest for **5-10 minutes** under a loose foil tent.
                        This allows the internal juices to redistribute, resulting in a tender and moister dish.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </div>

{% endblock %}
